`::shadow` is already supported (as well as any other `::identifier` and `:identifier(identifier)` stuff).
`/deep/` support may be too early since it's actually a combinator and most likely they will change it to something like `>>` or `>>>` (for example earlier [`^` and `^^`](https://github.com/less/less.js/issues/1801) support has been added and now where are these draft combinators? Gone :). And meanwhile it's always possible to generate whatever selector characters by escaping:

```
@deep: ~'/deep/';
x-foo @{deep} span {
    // ...
}
```

I guess there's nothing wrong with supporting a draft CSS feature in Less but not when the feature changes too often (yet).

issue.body:
When attempting to parse a CSS that uses new syntax /deep/ for Shadow DOM, the parser throws and error.  This causes an issue writing CSS for use with Polymer and web components.

Ex:

``` css
body /deep/ paper-button.positive {
  background: #4285f4;
}
```

Returns:

```
Parse error: Unrecognised input
body /deep/ paper-button.positive {  background: #4285f4;
```

See: http://dev.w3.org/csswg/css-scoping/#deep-combinator

